In TypeScript, you can use union types to represent a variable that could potentially be one of several types, but then use conditional types or utility types like `assert` to enforce that the variable is actually one specific type.

### Using Conditional Types (`typeof` assertions)
Conditional types allow you to create type guards based on conditions evaluated at runtime (though they do not execute those conditions). This can be used to ensure that an object has a specific property and its value adheres to a certain type. Here's an example:

```typescript
type IsDefined<T> = [T] extends [never] ? never : T;

// Check if a type is `string`
type IsString<T> = [T] extends [string] ? true : false;

// Usage:
function logValue<T>(value: IsDefined<T>, condition: IsString<T>) {
    if (condition) {
        console.log(`Value is a string: ${value}`);
    } else {
        console.error("Condition failed, value is not a string");
    }
}
```

### Using Utility Types (`assert`)
While TypeScript doesn't provide an `assert` type out of the box for type checking, you can implement a similar functionality using custom utility types:

```typescript
// Define a custom assert utility type
type Assert<T, U> = T extends U ? T : never;

// Usage:
type StringOrError = "Hello" | "World" | Error;

function processInput<T>(input: Assert<StringOrError, string>) {
    // Since input is asserted to be a string, it's safe to perform string operations here
    console.log(input.toUpperCase());
}

processInput("Hello"); // This will work fine
processInput(new Error("Unexpected error")); // This will cause a TypeScript compilation error
```

### Type Guards with `instanceof`
For objects, you can use `instanceof` as a simple type guard:

```typescript
class MyClass {}

function processMyClassInstance(instance: any) {
    if (instance instanceof MyClass) {
        // Now `instance` is safely cast to MyClass
        console.log("Processing MyClass instance");
    } else {
        console.error("Not a MyClass instance");
    }
}

const myInstance = new MyClass();
processMyClassInstance(myInstance); // This will work fine
processMyClassInstance("This should fail"); // This will cause a TypeScript compilation error
```

### Conclusion
By combining conditional types, utility types, and simple type guards, you can ensure that TypeScript enforces the type you expect even when the variable could theoretically belong to multiple types. Always ensure that such type assertions align with your program's runtime behavior to avoid unexpected errors.

